# Expo public variables for app/mobile
# Copy to .env (or .env.local) and fill values.
#
# --- TestFlight / App Store (EAS production) ---
# In Expo → Project → Environment variables → Production, set (no trailing slash on API):
#   EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://api.snaproad.app
#   API_URL=https://api.snaproad.app
#   EXPO_PUBLIC_MAPBOX_TOKEN, EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL, EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY,
#   EXPO_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY
# Then: cd app/mobile && npm run eas:build:prod:ios
# Railway API must return GET /health with "checks.database":"ok" (fix Supabase keys + migrations if degraded).
#
# To push local app/backend/.env + app/frontend/.env + app/mobile/.env into Expo (EAS) Production:
#   From repo root: npm run eas:sync-env   (requires `npx eas-cli login`; does not print secret values).

# API base (no trailing slash). For phone + tunnel dev:
# 1) Start backend: from repo root, `npm run dev:backend` (listens on :8001).
# 2) In a second terminal: `cd app/mobile && npm run tunnel:api`
# 3) Copy the https://....trycloudflare.com URL from the tunnel output into EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL below.
# 4) Restart Metro: `cd app/mobile && npm run start:dev:tunnel`
# Same Wi‑Fi (no tunnel): use http://YOUR_MAC_LAN_IP:8001
#
# If the dev client shows "Could not connect to development server", Expo needs the Metro URL explicitly.
# Prefer: `npm run start:dev:lan` from app/mobile (sets EXPO_PACKAGER_PROXY_URL automatically), or from repo root `npm run dev:mobile:lan`.
# Manual fix (shell, before expo start): export EXPO_PACKAGER_PROXY_URL=http://YOUR_MAC_LAN_IP:8081
#   and export REACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME=YOUR_MAC_LAN_IP
#
# If Expo shows "could not connect to development server" / "Tunnel connection has been closed" (ngrok):
#   From repo root: `npm run dev:mobile:lan` (backend + Expo --lan). Phone and Mac must be on the same Wi‑Fi.
#   Or keep --tunnel and set a free ngrok authtoken: https://dashboard.ngrok.com → `export NGROK_AUTH_TOKEN=...`
EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://REPLACE-WITH-trycloudflare-URL.trycloudflare.com
# Production / TestFlight local reference only — real values live in EAS Production env (see block above).
# EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://api.snaproad.app
# Let admin/partner profiles use the driver app (local Metro, dev client, or EAS preview — not store production).
# Preview builds use NODE_ENV=production; the app still allows staff when EAS_BUILD_PROFILE is preview/development.
# EXPO_PUBLIC_ALLOW_STAFF_IN_DRIVER_APP=true
EXPO_PUBLIC_MAPBOX_TOKEN=
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=
EXPO_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=

# Sentry (React Native). Public DSN only — safe to embed. Omit to disable Sentry.
# Create a React Native project in Sentry → Client Keys (DSN).
# EXPO_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN=https://xxxx@xxxx.ingest.sentry.io/xxxx
#
# For EAS release source maps / debug files, also set in Expo (secrets, not EXPO_PUBLIC_*):
#   SENTRY_ORG=your-org-slug
#   SENTRY_PROJECT=your-project-slug
#   SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN=sntrys_...   (from Sentry → Settings → Auth Tokens)

# --- EAS development build (Mapbox / native modules need a dev client, not Expo Go) ---
# From app/mobile: npx eas-cli login && npm run eas:build:dev:ios   (or :android)
# Install the build on device, then: npm run start:dev or start:dev:tunnel and open the app.

# Optional legacy aliases (app.config.ts reads these too)
# API_URL=
# MAPBOX_PUBLIC_TOKEN=
# SUPABASE_URL=
# SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=
# STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=
